Data Scienve project - Detection of Suspicious Transactions via Anomaly Detection (AML Project)

1. Project Overview
This project focuses on detecting suspicious financial transactions using anomaly detection techniques. The goal is to explore transaction patterns, identify unusual behavior, 
and evaluate different statistical and machine‑learning methods for AML (Anti‑Money Laundering) analysis.
2. Objectives
Perform exploratory data analysis (EDA) on transaction datasets
Detect anomalies using multiple methods
Compare the performance and interpretability of different approaches
Formulate and test hypotheses related to suspicious behavior
3. Data Sources
Due to file size constraints, this project uses a sample of the original datasets.

- **SAML-D:** 10000 rows sampled from the full dataset
- **IBM HI-Large:** 10000 rows sampled from HI-Large_Trans.csv

Full datasets available on Kaggle:
- [SAML-D](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/berkanoztas/synthetic-transaction-monitoring-dataset-aml)
- [IBM AML HI-Large](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/ealtman2019/ibm-transactions-for-anti-money-laundering-aml)
4. Methodology
The project follows a structured approach:
Data cleaning and preprocessing
Feature engineering (e.g. time, transaction behavior)
Statistical analysis
Anomaly detection using different techniques
5. Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)
EDA is used to understand transaction behavior and identify patterns:
Distribution of transaction amounts
Differences between normal and suspicious transactions
Detection of outliers and skewness
6. Hypothesis Testing
A statistical hypothesis test is performed to compare transaction amounts:
H₀: No significant difference between normal and suspicious transactions
H₁: Suspicious transactions have higher amounts
A Mann-Whitney U test is used due to non-normal data distribution.
7. Anomaly Detection Models
7. Anomaly Detection
The following methods are applied:
Z-score – detects extreme values
IQR – identifies statistical outliers
Isolation Forest – machine learning approach
8. Results
Transaction amount alone is not always a reliable indicator
Different datasets show different patterns
Machine learning methods perform better than simple statistical rules
